other_tests.findings: Small right pleural effusion, bibasilar atelectasis, transient mosaic enhancement of the liver parenchyma, mild periportal edema, trace upper abdominal ascites, stone in gallbladder neck now in gallbladder fundus with mild gallbladder wall edema, no intra or extrahepatic biliary dilatation, normal pancreas, normal spleen, unremarkable adrenal glands, normal kidneys with no hydronephrosis or masses, normal caliber of small and large bowel with fluid in transverse mesocolon and hyperenhancing mucosa of transverse colon suggesting mild transverse colitis, no retroperitoneal or mesenteric lymphadenopathy, normal abdominal aorta and patency of portal and hepatic veins.
other_tests.changes_over_time: Compared to the outside hospital CT, the radiodense stone in the gallbladder neck is now in the gallbladder fundus and the gallbladder is no longer distended.
